<tr data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-23" class="css-1c7mlbz eq9i9432">
<td data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-1" class="css-1akf6pt eq9i9434">改革历程</td>
<td data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-3" class="css-1akf6pt eq9i9434">Prisoner of the State: The Secret Journal of Premier Zhao Ziyang</td>
<td data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-5" class="css-1akf6pt eq9i9434">趙紫陽 / Zhao Ziyang</td>
<td data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-7" class="css-1akf6pt eq9i9434">2009</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div></div>
</div><h3 type="h3" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e14khtrb0 css-17x7qa9 e793b7w1"><strong data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-0" class="css-1mniedq eq9i94316">The ‘backbone’ of a democratic web</strong></h3><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">IPFS developer Protocol Labs describes its peer-to-peer web technology as the backbone of Web3. It is just one of many decentralised storage protocols touting a Web3 future – Storj, Swarm, and Arweave are some of the other popular options – but IPFS has so far garnered the most attention.</p><div datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1xdhyk6 e1346ty30">While much of the conversation around Web3 centres around blockchain-based use cases, mostly involving <a class="euc41pk0 e13op9j60 e1qbu6wp1 css-jgjyn2 ef1hf1w0" href="https://www.scmp.com/topics/digital-currencies?module=inline&amp;pgtype=article" data-qa="BaseLink-renderAnchor-StyledAnchor"><span data-qa="Component-Text" class="css-0 e1qbu6wp0">cryptocurrencies</span></a> and <a class="euc41pk0 e13op9j60 e1qbu6wp1 css-jgjyn2 ef1hf1w0" href="https://www.scmp.com/topics/nfts?module=inline&amp;pgtype=article" data-qa="BaseLink-renderAnchor-StyledAnchor"><span data-qa="Component-Text" class="css-0 e1qbu6wp0">non-fungible tokens (NFTs)</span></a>, IPFS is not itself based on blockchain (unlike Protocol Labs’ adjacent product Filecoin). Whereas blockchain is ill-suited for large file distribution, IPFS makes it easy for computers to share files of any size directly with each other, no central server necessary.</div><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Similar to the widely used file-sharing protocol BitTorrent, IPFS identifies each file by its unique hash value, which can then be fetched from any connected node that is sharing that file.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Like blockchain, though, the decentralised nature of IPFS and the ethos of those using it is at odds with the reality that widespread adoption has concentrated much of its usage in the hands of large organisations running the servers that keep the network running smoothly. Ironically, it is the more centralised gateway servers that have made IPFS so effective at bypassing the Great Firewall.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Since IPFS is open source, anyone is free to set up their own gateway on any domain. That means that while some gateways are already blocked in China, others are not. A new gateway could spring up tomorrow that would take time for Chinese censors to notice and subsequently block.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Some gateways are set up on critical internet infrastructure, such as servers from Cloudflare or Amazon Web Services. Chinese authorities are cautious about mass blocking IP addresses from these servers, as it can break the flow of internet traffic and harm accessibility to important resources for developers.</p><div class="methode-html-wrapper oembed-wrapper e1kkz63z0 css-1llrc1m ecv2zmr0" data-qa="Component-renderMap-StyledDiv">
<div class=" e1yzzwz60 css-1p2dind e132il0u0" data-qa="Component-SCMPYoutubeVideoContainer"><div data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewContainer" class="css-1bv0tuz eaw92su7"><img data-qa="BaseImage-handleRenderImage-StyledImage" class="eaw92su8 css-1beh2bb em4672x0" loading="lazy" src="https://cdn.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/styles/wide_landscape/public/d8/video/thumbnail/2019/04/24/thumbnail_clean.jpg?itok=eGpcsOr9"/><div data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewContentContainer" class="css-1xvf7af eaw92su6"><div data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewContentFloatContainer" class="css-n8rr8l eaw92su3"><div data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewPlayButtonContainer" class="css-1xyu478 eaw92su4"><svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-StyledPlayButton" class="css-0 eaw92su5"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><circle fill="#ffca05" opacity="0.802" cx="20" cy="20" r="20"></circle><path fill="#FFF" d="M29 20l-14 8V12z"></path></g></svg></div><div data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewContentDataContainer" class="css-1akwka eaw92su0"><p data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewDuration" class="css-dkee4u eaw92su1">02:33</p><p data-qa="SCMPYoutubeVideoPreview-PreviewTitle" class="css-1ajvbe4 eaw92su2">How China censors the internet</p></div></div></div></div><div class="e132il0u1 css-n8zt3b e473b3v0" data-qa="SCMPYouTubeVideoFooter-VideoTitleContainer"><svg width="14" height="19" viewBox="0 0 14 9" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" data-qa="SCMPYouTubeVideoFooter-StyledVideoRecorder" class="css-1ckj6g e473b3v1"><path d="M10.889 3.375V.75c0-.412-.35-.75-.778-.75H.778C.35 0 0 .338 0 .75v7.5c0 .412.35.75.778.75h9.333c.428 0 .778-.338.778-.75V5.625l3.111 3V.375l-3.111 3z" fill="#6f6f6f"></path></svg><div data-qa="SCMPYouTubeVideoFooter-VideoTitle" class="css-0 e473b3v2">How China censors the internet</div></div></div></div><div datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1xdhyk6 e1346ty30">China’s brief <a class="euc41pk0 e13op9j60 e1qbu6wp1 css-jgjyn2 ef1hf1w0" href="https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1134717/programmers-angry-over-blocking-github-code-sharing-site?module=inline&amp;pgtype=article" data-qa="BaseLink-renderAnchor-StyledAnchor"><span data-qa="Component-Text" class="css-0 e1qbu6wp0">ban of GitHub in 2013</span></a> illustrated this point: widespread outrage from programmers over no longer being able to access the most widely used platform for open source code repositories resulted in a rare reversal for Beijing censors.</div><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">These censorship-resistant properties have led some to argue that the Web3 future favours transparency and democracy. Anthony Vinci, an adjunct senior fellow at the Centre for a New American Security, and Nadia Schadlow, a fellow at the Hudson Institute and the Hoover Institution, argued in <em data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-1" class="css-1mniedq eq9i94315">The Washington Post</em> in January that Web3 could erode China’s data dominance and authoritarian rule.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">“Conceptually, Web3 is innately more beneficial to Western liberal democracies, which value democracy and personal privacy,” the scholars wrote.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">The argument hinges on the idea that “authoritarian states cannot abide private life because that’s where anti-governmental activities can percolate”. Web3 makes it hard to monitor and control the flow of information. Moreover, without any centralised databases from which to scoop up user data, China’s data dominance owing to its vast population could be eroded, according to the authors.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">However, Vinci and Schadlow did not offer any theory for how Web3 would avoid the fate of Web 1.0 or Web 2.0 in China. The government, which supports the development of blockchain, may be betting on its ability to eventually control the flow of information in a Web3 world just as it has on previous versions of the web.</p><h3 type="h3" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e14khtrb0 css-17x7qa9 e793b7w1"><a class="link-text css-e0dnmk ef1hf1w0" href="https://www.scmp.com/tech/policy/article/3119095/nailing-jell-o-wall-how-china-wants-keep-controlling-internet?module=hard_link&amp;pgtype=article" style="inline-size:100%" data-qa="BaseLink-renderAnchor-StyledAnchor"><div data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-RootContainer" class=" css-iqvku8 eeeqn936"><div data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-LeftContainer" class="css-1q3ym6v eeeqn935"><div data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-TitleContainer" class="css-pcbgty eeeqn931"><span data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-TitleText" class="css-66qo9a eeeqn932">Nailing Jell-O to the wall: new rules reveal China’s vision for internet control</span></div><div data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-UpdatedDateContainer" class="css-1jao69x eeeqn930"></div></div><div data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-RightContainer" class="css-0 eeeqn934"><div data-qa="DigitalArchiveLink-ImageContainer" class="css-12nlsj4 eeeqn933"></div></div></div></a></h3><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Some Chinese companies have already been vocal in their support for IPFS as an innovative new technology, but they have couched their support in cautious language. At the Digital Infrastructure Forum in Beijing last December, multiple companies in the industry signed a “declaration on IPFS industry self-discipline”, calling for the “healthy and orderly development” of the industry and related enterprises to exercise “social responsibility”.</p><h3 type="h3" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e14khtrb0 css-17x7qa9 e793b7w1"><strong data-qa="ContentSchemaRender-defaultRenderMapFunctions-Component-0" class="css-1mniedq eq9i94316">Serendipitous censorship</strong></h3><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">However the Chinese government responds to the development of Web3 technologies, the most effective form of censorship may already be firmly in place. Many in China are happy staying within the walled gardens of Chinese platforms, never venturing past the Great Firewall where they could unexpectedly stumble across banned content.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">“I would say LibGen’s use of IPFS doesn’t have a lot of impact on those who use LibGen a lot, because they’re used to VPNs anyway,” said James, the LibGen bot operator. “But it might be helpful to share what’s on Libgen. Platforms like Matters use IPFS to try to avoid censorship and takedowns.”</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Matters.news is a news platform that distributes content over IPFS.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">There are still some signs that LibGen’s popularity is growing in China, based on the number of downloads from Sci-Hub, which shares resources with LibGen.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">Alexandra Elbakyan, the creator of the platform that fetches scientific papers from publishers using shared credentials, posted download numbers on Twitter on February 12 showing that downloads in China far outpaced those in other countries in the previous 30 days. Chinese IP addresses downloaded about 337.2 million articles, while the US had the second-highest number at 126.7 million. Elbakyanʼs Twitter account has since been removed.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">“I think Library Genesis and Sci-Hub more or less move on the same path,” Bodó said. “In the latest Sci-Hub data, what I see is China is leading by far in terms of usage.”</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">When it comes to accessing the IPFS network directly, though, there are already signs that Chinese censors are fighting back. Some users on GitHub complained about the Great Firewall blocking access to IPFS nodes and throttling traffic. The main issue appears to be the firewall’s ability to identify certain types of traffic and then cut off access to those servers.</p><div class="image-inline-container e1kkz63z0 css-1llrc1m ecv2zmr0" data-qa="Component-renderMap-StyledDiv"><div data-qa="Component-Container" class="css-bjn8wh e1xb2kle0"><figure class="image-inline caption e76tpiq0 e1xb2kle1 css-18ms6eb eope0cl0" data-qa="ArticleImage-ArticleImageContainer"><div data-qa="ArticleImage-ImageContainer" class="css-0 eope0cl3"><img data-qa="BaseImage-handleRenderImage-StyledImage" class="eope0cl2 css-3q8izr em4672x0" loading="lazy" src="https://cdn.i-scmp.com/sites/default/files/d8/images/canvas/2022/03/30/14907e82-340a-4f84-aa27-56c66d426062_92e284f5.jpg" title="Tor, another type of decentralised web technology, is routinely blocked in China. When nodes are no longer directly accessible through a relay, users can choose to connect via a bridge, an unlisted connection that helps circumvent censorship."/></div><figcaption data-qa="ArticleImage-DescriptionContainer" class="css-6potyr eope0cl1">Tor, another type of decentralised web technology, is routinely blocked in China. When nodes are no longer directly accessible through a relay, users can choose to connect via a bridge, an unlisted connection that helps circumvent censorship.</figcaption></figure></div></div><div datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1xdhyk6 e1346ty30">There is also nothing fundamentally new about decentralised web technologies. Tor, perhaps the most widely known of these technologies because of notorious darknet platforms like the <a class="euc41pk0 e13op9j60 e1qbu6wp1 css-jgjyn2 ef1hf1w0" href="https://www.scmp.com/news/world/article/1323183/online-drug-marketplace-silk-road-shut-down-fbi-arrest-owner?module=inline&amp;pgtype=article" data-qa="BaseLink-renderAnchor-StyledAnchor"><span data-qa="Component-Text" class="css-0 e1qbu6wp0">Silk Road marketplace</span></a>, was developed by the United States Naval Research Laboratory in the 1990s and became an independent project in 2002.</div><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">China has blocked access to Tor nodes for years. This has given rise to new obfuscation methods to hide the traffic, but it is often slow and not widely used in China. An average of about 1,500 people connected to Tor from Chinese IP addresses daily in March using a bridge, or unlisted connections that help circumvent blocking. The number of relay and bridge users connecting from China is down by about 30 per cent from the daily average in March last year, similar to user numbers five years ago.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">This raises questions about whether Web3 is really the win for democracy that some cryptocurrency evangelists believe.</p><p datatype="p" data-qa="Component-Component" class="e15kmbpe0 css-1c6uqr6 e1346ty31">“Web 3.0 is a political project with a political goal,” Bodó said. “You can wrap IPFS into the Web 3.0 discourse, but then Web 3.0 disappears. Technologies to share local storage will still remain because that’s independent of the everyday political projects of how we can decentralise everything and bypass the state.”</p><div class="js-reading-100-percent-completion-tracker css-19icq8a e1gsc5vp0" data-qa="useTrackViewedPercentageRender-trackViewedPercentageRenders-TrackPercentageBlock"></div></section><div class=" e1oct4f914 piano-metering__paywall-container css-1e938sv eswswyw1" data-qa="ArticlePaywallContainer-Container"><div data-qa="ArticlePaywallContainer-LoadingContainer" class="css-hu4lls eswswyw2"><div class="css-1px2vm1 e1omqzrn0" data-qa="Loading-CenteredContainer"><img aria-label="loading" data-qa="BaseImage-handleRenderImage-StyledImage" loading="eager" src="https://assets-v2.i-scmp.com/production/_next/static/media/wheel-on-gray.af4a55f9.gif" class="css-1vuis1k em4672x0"/></div></div><div class="article-view__piano-metering css-16o2qwc eswswyw0" data-qa="ArticlePaywallContainer-Wrapper"></div></div></div><div data-qa="GenericArticle-CommentAndReaction" class="css-rkwuww eg5341w14"></div><div data-qa="GenericArticle-MoreOnThis" class="css-19rwy8z eg5341w12"></div><div data-qa="GenericArticle-AuthorDetail" class="css-gjw4x4 eg5341w11"></div><div data-qa="GenericArticle-Topic" class="css-t8ywx4 eg5341w10"></div><div data-qa="GenericArticle-Left" class="css-1pbnq3j eg5341w28"><aside class=" e1oct4f912 css-o3nfvy e1l7a8ud2" data-qa="ArticleShareWidget-Container"><div data-qa="ArticleSpeechInlineWidgetGeneric-Wrapper" class="css-kqjje6 egghhyv1"><div class="e1l7a8ud1 css-1lzigxg e9t53i10" data-qa="EmptyButton-Container"><div data-qa="EmptyButton-IconWrapper" class="css-1duflnb e9t53i12"><svg width="28" height="24" viewBox="0 0 28 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" data-qa="EmptyButton-StyledIcon" class="css-ozd7xs e9t53i11"><path d="M14 1C11.6131 1 9.32387 1.96119 7.63604 3.67211C5.94821 5.38304 5 7.70355 5 10.1232V17.0607C5.00017 17.575 5.20179 18.0681 5.56053 18.4318C5.91928 18.7955 6.4058 18.9998 6.91314 19H8.30043C8.80788 19 9.29457 18.7957 9.65345 18.432C10.0123 18.0683 10.214 17.5751 10.2142 17.0607V13.4948C10.2142 13.2401 10.1647 12.9879 10.0685 12.7525C9.97234 12.5172 9.83136 12.3034 9.65364 12.1233C9.47592 11.9432 9.26494 11.8004 9.03275 11.7029C8.80057 11.6055 8.55172 11.5554 8.30043 11.5555H7.22364V10.1219C7.22364 8.30006 7.93758 6.55288 9.20839 5.26468C10.4792 3.97648 12.2028 3.25277 14 3.25277C15.7972 3.25277 17.5208 3.97648 18.7916 5.26468C20.0624 6.55288